






          There are 3 input vector types. The first is  a  general  PCM   set
          consisting  of  various sinusoidal  inputs; this set is the 'normal
          input'. The second set of inputs or 'overload  input'  consists  of
          very  high  level  PCM  signals. The  third  set  is denoted as 'i-
          input' and is an ADPCM sequence that exercises the algorithm  in  a
          manner that is not possible   with  a  PCM input  sequence.

          This diskette contains 34 files as follows:

            1.  NRM.M, the PCM normal mu-law input sequence of 16384 values.

            2.  OVR.M, the PCM overload mu-law input sequence of 2048 values.

            3.  I16, I24, I32, I40: the ADPCM input sequences for operation at 
                16, 24, 32 and 40 kbit/s

            4.  28 ADPCM or PCM outputs (including cross-vectors) of an ADPCM
                implementation  starting   from  reset.

          All test sequence files are in  ASCII  notation.   Each  value  (or
          sample)  of  every   file uses  hexadecimal  representation  with 2
          hex characters for each 8 bit value.   Every  line  in  every  file
          contains  32 values (or 64 characters) and is terminated by a  line
          feed character.  For  files containing  x  bit  ADPCM  values,  the
          (8-x) most  significant bits are set to 0.  Two more hex characters
          representing a checksum computation  over the   entire   file   are
          appended   to   the   end  of  each  file.  Checksum is computed by
          summing every sample value (two hex characters  comprise  a  sample
          value)  in   the   file  and   then   finding  the  remainder  when
          divided by 255. The following Table  describes  the  test  sequence
